passages.text: Rising Through the Stories

"We are such stuff as dreams are made on, and our little life is rounded with a sleep." (The Tempest, Act IV, Scene 1). The past season echoed Prospero's words: a rally built less on earnings substance than on sentiment, flows, and a sense of optimism. Healthcare and Tech faltered, REITs and Discretionary led the charge, and the market overall gained. Earnings downgrades persisted through the month, with only \(17\%\) of companies seeing upgrades post results.

Gale force volatility - Over \(30\%\) of the ASX 50 moved by more than \(+ / - 3z\) on result day. A number of 'blue chips' suffered record or near-record on- day declines - CSL, JHX and WOW in particular. Dramatic moves to the upside were also a regular feature of the season, with BXB, COL and QAN all gaining \(9\% +\) on- day. As we anticipated in our result season preview (link), Aug- 25 set another record for volatility (see Figure 3), with nearly a third of the index moving by more than \(3z\) .

Earnings caught in the downdraft - EPS forecasts were cut across all but one sector (REITs) on a rolling post- result basis. With share prices on the rise, this translated to a \(0.54x\) P/E multiple expansion through August. The chart to the right highlights the largest P/E moves through the month. While we aren't singularly bearish - noting our REIT, Discretionary, Materials OWs - there is clear valuation stretch apparent in several segments of the market. Banks carry much of the downside embedded in our weighted index target; our team's average price target implies \(15\%\) downside across the majors.

A foul wind blows from the west - A troubling feature of this season was the trials and tribulations encountered by a range of companies with offshore operations. The malaise particularly afflicted those with US exposures, including AMC, CSL, JHX, REH and RWC. Even those doing well in the US market, notably BXB, pointed to soft and challenging macro conditions.

Beats and misses: an even balance - Our team's forecast for the beat/miss ratio (note) was again close to the mark. Their prediction was for an elevated proportion of in- line results, which proved to be the case. Misses outnumbered the beats and downside reaction to falling short \((- 6.2\%)\) , rel) was more than double the upside reaction to beats \((+2.9\%)\) rel).

"We are such stuff as dreams are made on, and our little life is rounded with a sleep." (The Tempest, Act IV, Scene 1). The past season echoed Prospero's words: a rally built less on earnings substance than on sentiment, flows, and a sense of optimism.

Healthcare and Tech faltered, REITs and Discretionary led the charge, and the market overall gained. Earnings downgrades persisted through the month, albeit with an unusual deceleration in the final week.
Approximately \(30\%\) of the ASX 50 moved by more than \(+ / - 3z\) on result day. A number of 'blue chips' suffered record or near- record on- day declines.
Figure 3: ASX 50 | On-day stock moves of \(+ / - 3z\)
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
CSL, JHX and WOW in particular felt the brunt of the market's ire, all dropping by well over \(10\%\) on their respective result days.
Dramatic moves to the upside were also a regular feature of the season, with BXB, COL and QAN all gaining by \(9\% +\) on- day.
Figure 4: Sharp moves across the ASX 50
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.
As we highlighted in our mid- season Dissector, a key factor in this escalating volatility is declining trading velocity in the ASX 50.
Figure 5: Declining trading velocity is undoubtedly a factor
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
Violent share price moves haven't been confined to the ASX 50; the ASX 200 also set a record for moves greater than 3σ in a result month.
Figure 6: ASX 200| On-day stock moves of +/- 3σ
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.
A feature of this results season has been the pain endured by companies with offshore operations, particularly in the US.
Figure 7: Pain in the west
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.

In contrast, many of the season's top performers are more domestically focused operators, with two of the major banks gracing the ranks of ASX 100 leaders on a post result rolling basis (relative). key exceptions include BXB, CAR, ANN and WOR.
Figure 8: ASX 100 | Top performers (post result rolling, relative)
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.
Across the ex- 100, a mixed bag of domestic and offshore names topped the table, with Discretionary and REITs having the highest representation.
Figure 9: Ex-100 | Top performers rolling post result (rel)
Source:Bloomberg Finance L.P.
While some sectors are pointing to a healthy price and volume environment, the skew across the season has been for downgrades to Sales estimates.
Figure 10: Revenue forecasts scaled back through August (consensus)
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P. estimates.

A feature of results season in recent years has been persistent downward pressure on operating margins. There is little to suggest that this is abating. On our analysis, margins have been downgraded across every sector, bar Tech, since July. The sharpest pressure has been on the top- line, where consensus downgrades have been widespread. The blow has been softened, in part, by ongoing efforts to drive down costs. On our count, there have been over 100 references this season to soft, weak or challenging operating conditions
Figure 11: Margin pressure | Downgrades post result
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.

In characteristic fashion, analysts downgraded year- ahead earnings across the majority of sectors in August. As evident in the headline upgrade/downgrade ratio, the overall direction of earnings is down. For the ASX 50, FY26 projections have been scaled back by \(c.1\%\) . Australia sits firmly at the bottom of the global EPS revisions table in the YTD.
Figure 12: Global | EPS Revisions (1M)
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
At a sector level, only REITS saw EPS upgrades through the season, with all other sectors sliding backwards.
Figure 13: AU GICS | EPS Revisions (rolling post result, consensus)
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.

With earnings falling but share prices rising, we're seeing another season of pronounced multiple expansion. At an index level, Aug- 25 marks the second- largest increase in one- year forward multiples in the last 15 years.
Figure 14: ASX 200 | P/E multiple expansion in results season (Aug)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.
Another month of multiple expansion puts Australia further 'ahead' in the extent to which key indices are deviating from long- term P/E averages.

Figure 17: P/E expansion | Top 20

Beats, Misses & Upgrades, DowngradesIn terms of the beat/miss ratio, Discretionary and Financials generated the highest rate of beats. Staples, Tech and Utilities ended the season with zero beats. At an aggregate level, in-line results were again elevated vs history, indicative of a more stable post- COVID earnings backdrop. Notably, however, the rate of beats did lag those of misses.
Figure 19: ASX 200 | Beat/Miss Ratio
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P. "Note: Based on \(>2\%\) delta for beats and \(Figure 20: ASX 200 | Upgrade/Downgrade Ratio

Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P. "Note: Based on \(>2\%\) change for upgrades and \(2\%\) ) outperformed sharply (290bp). Those that reported in- line results performed in line with the market, while those that missed sharply underperformed.
Figure 21: Relative price performance and consensus EPS change since result (average)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.
Companies that beat expectations saw double the P/E point expansion of those that missed or reported in- line earnings.
Figure 22: P/E expansion/(contraction) since result (average)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Bloomberg Finance L.P.
From the outset of August, our team's bottom- up projection for aggregated FY26 index EPS has fallen by \(1.1\%\) . Only two sectors have seen upgrades, being:

HUB: more favourable cost outcomes, strong lead indicators SDF: uplift in organic earnings growth and acquisition contributions WBC: \(5\%\) lift in FY26 estimates, uptick in core NIM forecast and loan growth
LLC: large upgrades related to project realisations MGR: uplift in development segment EBIT SGP: stronger pick up in resi settlements
At the other end of the spectrum, downgrades have been concentrated in:
WTC: slower revenue growth, CargoWise guidance, E2 open timing DDR: slowing top- line momentum
CSL: delayed cost savings, Behring weakness, slower gross margin recovery RHC: weakness in the AU business (Joonadalup)
CAR: margin downgrades due to strategic investments in marketing and product development TLS: competition, churn, consumer shift to pre- paid
Figure 23: JPME FY26 EPS revisions (MTD)
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.
Our bottom- up FY26 EPS growth forecast now stands at a modest \(+2.3\%\) . On an ex- Materials, Financials and Energy basis, the figure is a more respectable \(+6.7\%\) .
Figure 24: JPME FY26 EPS index growth bridge | ASX 200
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.
Figure 25: JPME FY26 ex-Materials, Financials & Energy | ASX 200
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.
Figure 26: JPMc CY26 index growth bridge | ASX 200
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates.

The earnings outlook for the ASX 200 CY25- 27 has been sliding in the YTD. Results season has brought about another step- down, particularly in CY26. Our earnings growth projection for CY26 is 100bp below consensus.
Figure 27: Consensus CY26 index growth | ASX 200
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
The US remains a clear leader in terms of forward earnings growth.
Figure 28: Consensus CY26 index growth | S&P 500
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.

On a blended forward 12- month basis, upward EPS revisions are running at a lower rate vs downgrades. On average, \(14\%\) companies have seen earnings upgrades since their results, vs \(41\%\) seeing downgrades. The average rolling 12- month forward EPS revision is at \(- 3.1\%\) (JPM: \(- 1.6\%\) ). Financials is the only sector seeing net consensus earnings upgrades.
Figure 32: Consensus earnings revisions | Blended forward 12M
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
Blended forward 12- month DPS revisions skew negative, with only \(26\%\) seeing upgrades vs \(33\%\) in downgrade mode. The average rolling DPS revision is at \(- 2.2\%\) (JPM: \(- 0.5\%\) ).
Figure 33: Consensus dividend revisions | Blended forward 12M
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P.
